0, 4], [0, 5], [1, 2], [1, 3], [1, 4], [1, 5], [1, 6], [2, 3], [2, 4], [2, 5], [2, 6], [3, 4], [3, 5], [3, 6], [4, 5], [4, 6], [5, 6]]"}, {"input": "text = \"abcdabcdabcd\", words = [\"abcd\",\"bcda\",\"cdab\",\"dabc\",\"abcdabcd\"]", "output": "[[0, 3], [0, 7], [1, 4], [2, 5], [3, 6], [4, 7], [4, 11], [5, 8], [6, 9], [7, 10], [8, 11]]"}], "query": "You are an expert Python programmer. You will be given a question (problem specification) and will generate a correct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nGiven a string text and an array of strings words, return an array of all index pairs [i, j] so that the substring text[i...j] is in words.\nReturn the pairs [i, j] in sorted order (i.e., sort them by their first coordinate, and in case of ties sort them by their second coordinate).\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: text = \"thestoryofleetcodeandme\", words = [\"story\",\"fleet\",\"leetcode\"]\nOutput: [[3,7],[9,13],[10,17]]\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: text = \"ababa\", words = [\"aba\",\"ab\"]\nOutput: [[0,1],[0,2],[2,3],[2,4]]\nExplanation: Notice that matches can overlap, see \"aba\" is found in [0,2] and [2,4].\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= text.length <= 100\n1 <= words.length <= 20\n1 <= words[i].length <= 50\ntext and words[i] consist of lowercase English letters.\nAll the strings of words are unique.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def indexPairs(self, text: str, words: List[str]) -> List[List[int]]:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def indexPairs(self, text: str, words: List[str]) -> List[List[int]]:\n        words = set(words)\n        n = len(text)\n        return sorted(\n            [[i, j] for i in range(n) for j in range(i, n) if text[i : j + 1] in words]\n        )\n```\n\nThis solution uses a set for `words` to allow O(1) average time complexity for membership checks. It then iterates over all possible substrings of `text` and checks if they are in the set of `words`. If they are, it adds the starting and ending indices to the result list. Finally, it sorts the list of index pairs before returning it.", "estimated_date": 1558828800000}